\[
\frac{9}{60} = 0.15 \text{ hours}.
\]  
The distance is then:  
\[
20 \, \text{km/h} \times 0.15 \, \text{hours} = 3 \, \text{km}.
\]  

When cycling at 6 km/h, the time required is:  
\[
\frac{3 \, \text{km}}{6 \, \text{km/h}} = 0.5 \, \text{hours}.
\]  
Converting 0.5 hours back to minutes:  
\[
0.5 \times 60 = 30 \, \text{minutes}.
\]  

Using the inverse proportion method confirms this result:  
\[
\text{Time}_{\text{cycle}} = \text{Time}_{\text{drive}} \times \frac{\text{Speed}_{\text{drive}}}{\text{Speed}_{\text{cycle}}} = 9 \times \frac{20}{6} = 30 \, \text{minutes}.
\]  

The correct answer is **A**.  

Answer: A
